# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: solid-propellant-rocket
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/9k720-iskander] The **9K720 Iskander** (Russian: «Искандер»; NATO reporting name **SS-26 Stone**) is a family of Russian mobile short-range ballistic missile systems.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/9k720-iskander] The basic M model has a range of 500 kilometres (270 nmi; 310 mi).
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/9k720-iskander] It was intended to replace the OTR-21 Tochka in the Russian military by 2020.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/9k720-iskander] The Iskander has several different conventional warheads, including a cluster munitions warhead, a fuel–air explosive enhanced-blast warhead, a high-explosive fragmentation warhead, an earth penetrator for bunker busting and an electromagnetic pulse device for anti-radar missions.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/9k720-iskander] The missile can also carry nuclear warheads.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/9k720-iskander] In September 2017, the KB Mashinostroyeniya (KBM) general designer Valery M.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/9k720-iskander] Kashin said that there were at least seven types of missiles (and "perhaps more") for Iskander, including one cruise missile.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/9k720-iskander] The road-mobile Iskander was the second attempt by Russia to replace the Scud missile.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/9k720-iskander] The first attempt, the OTR-23 Oka, was eliminated under the INF Treaty.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/9k720-iskander] The design work on Iskander was begun in December 1988, initially directed by the KBM rocket weaponry designer Sergey Nepobedimy, and was not significantly affected by the dissolution of the USSR in 1991.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/9k720-iskander] The first successful launch occurred in 1996.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/9k720-iskander] In September 2004, at a meeting with senior defense officials reporting to President Vladimir Putin on the drafting of a defense budget for 2005, the Russian Defence Minister Sergei Ivanov spoke about the completion of static tests of a new tactical missile system called the Iskander.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/9k720-iskander] He said that the system would go into quantity production in 2005 and toward the end of that year, Russia would have a brigade armed with it.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/9k720-iskander] In March 2005, a source in the Russian defence industry told Interfax-AVN the development of new missiles with a range of 500–600 kilometres (270–320 nmi; 310–370 mi), based on existing Iskander-E tactical missile systems, was a possibility.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/9k720-iskander] He said, however, that it "may take up to five or six years".
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/9k720-iskander] In 2006, serial production of the Iskander-M tactical ballistic missile system was launched, and the system was adopted by the Russian army.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/9k720-iskander] The production cost of the missile system was reported in 2014 to have been slashed by a third by cutting the 20% markup applied by the missile manufacturer at each stage of the components supply chain from a cumulative 810% to markup of 21% applied only to the finished product.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/9k720-iskander] In November 2016, the Russian military announced that the modernization of the Iskander-M system was underway.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/9k720-iskander] A number of countries were reported to have shown interest in purchasing the export version of Iskander, but such possibility was only announced in early February 2017.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/9k720-iskander] The United States has argued that the 9M728/9M729 (SSC-X-7/SSC-X-8) cruise missiles used by Iskander-K violates the INF Treaty because their estimated range is beyond 500 kilometres (270 nmi; 310 mi).
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/9k720-iskander] The general director of the company-developer of the system said in April 2024 that the precision of the missile has been improved since the start of the Russian invasion of Ukraine.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/9k720-iskander] The Iskander-M system is equipped with two solid-propellant single-stage guided missiles, model **9M723K1**.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/9k720-iskander] The missiles are controlled throughout the entire flight path and fitted with an inseparable warhead.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/9k720-iskander] The missiles can reportedly be re-targeted during flight in the case of engaging mobile targets.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/9k720-iskander] Another unique feature of Iskander-M is the optically guided warhead, which can also be controlled by encrypted radio transmission, including such as those from AWACS or UAV.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/9k720-iskander] During boost phase, thrust vector control (TVC) is accomplished by graphite vanes similar in layout to the V-2 and Scud series tactical ballistic missiles.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/9k720-iskander] The missile is reportedly controlled during the whole flight with gas-dynamic and aerodynamic control surfaces, using small fins to reduce its radar signature.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/9k720-iskander] At least some versions are equipped with decoys in order to aid in penetrating missile defense systems.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/9k720-iskander] Iskander is a tactical missile system designed to be used in theater level conflicts.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/9k720-iskander] In 2007, a new missile for the system (and launcher) was test fired, the R-500 cruise missile, with a range of applications up to 2000 km or more.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/9k720-iskander] In 2018, the Iskander missile reportedly gained the capability to strike static sea targets.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/9k720-iskander] In 2020 it was said that the MAZ was the primary supplier for the chassis of the launchers for the Iskander-M because the domestic Russian products are of comparatively low quality.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/9k720-iskander] The system can be transported by various vehicles, including airplanes.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/9k720-iskander] When nuclear armed, the warhead is estimated to have a yield of 5 to 50 kilotonnes of TNT (21 to 209 TJ) (Iskander-M).
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/9k720-iskander] Variant for the Russian Armed Forces with two **9M723** quasi-ballistic missiles with a confirmed range of 400 km (250 miles), published range of 415 km (258 miles), and rumored range of 500 km (310 miles).
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/9k720-iskander] Speed Mach 6–7, flight altitude up to 6–50 km, nuclear capable missile, controlled at all stages, not ballistic flight path.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/9k720-iskander] Immediately after the launch and upon approach to the target, the missile can perform maneuvering to evade anti-ballistic missiles.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/9k720-iskander] "K" for *Krylataya* ("Winged") (Russian: крылатая ракета).
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/9k720-iskander] Variant intended to carry various types of cruise missiles (Russian: крылатая ракета; literally winged rocket).
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/9k720-iskander] The director of the state corporation Rostec Sergey Chemezov commented that the Iskander missile complex is a serious offensive weapon capable of carrying a nuclear warhead.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/9k720-iskander] In 2016, Armenia, a Russian ally and a member of the Collective Security Treaty Organization (CSTO) became the first foreign country to operate the system.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/9k720-iskander] Iskander-E has a maximum range up to 280 km, to comply with Missile Technology Control Regime restrictions for export, and is fitted with a simplified inertial guidance system.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/9k720-iskander] It flies on a flattened trajectory under 50 km altitude, allowing aerodynamic steering using tail fins, permitting a less predictable flight path and accurate delivery.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/9k720-iskander] The system can also use missiles carrying warheads with cluster munitions.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/9k720-iskander] The first documented use of the Iskander was in the Russo-Georgian War in which Dutch journalist Stan Storimans was killed on 12 August 2008 in Gori.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/9k720-iskander] An investigation by the Dutch government revealed that a single, 5 mm fragment from an anti-personnel sub-munition, carried by an Iskander missile, killed the Dutch journalist.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/9k720-iskander] In September 2009, the Russian military announced plans to deploy Iskander missiles in all the military districts of Russia "in a short time".
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/9k720-iskander] According to the Stratfor report in 2010 there were five Iskander brigades stationed and operational in Russia, namely the 26th Rocket Brigade in the town of Luga, Leningrad Oblast, south of St.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/9k720-iskander] In June 2013, it was revealed that Russia had deployed several Iskander-M ballistic missile systems in Armenia at undisclosed locations.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/9k720-iskander] In 2016, it was reported by media that Armenia had received a *divizion* of Iskander missiles.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/9k720-iskander] Russian Foreign Ministry officials declared the right to deploy nuclear weapons in the peninsula, which is generally recognized as part of Ukraine, in December 2014 and June 2015.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/9k720-iskander] In March 2016, at least one Iskander system was reportedly deployed at Russia's Hmeimim airbase in Syria.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/9k720-iskander] In January 2017 an Israeli company claimed satellite photography confirmed the Syrian deployment.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/9k720-iskander] According to a Fox News report in early February 2017, four Iskander missiles had been fired at opposition targets in the Idlib province in Syria.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/9k720-iskander] During the 2022 Russian invasion of Ukraine, Russia launched several Iskander missiles over their border into Ukraine as part of their assault.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/9k720-iskander] These missiles demonstrated a previously unknown capability that employed decoys to confuse air defense systems.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/9k720-iskander] It is believed this technology was kept a closely guarded secret, and not included on Iskander missiles exported outside of Russia.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/9k720-iskander] From 23 April 2022, Russia deployed more units equipped with Iskander-M to the Belgorod Oblast, as close as 60 km from the border of Ukraine.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/9k720-iskander] In March 2023, Ukrainian Air Force spokesman Yuri Ihnat reported that Ukraine was unable to shoot down Iskander ballistic missiles.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/9k720-iskander] However, on 29 May, Ukraine claimed to have destroyed 11 Iskander missiles of both the ballistic and cruise missile variants.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/9k720-iskander] On 5 March 2024, it was confirmed that a M142 HIMARS was destroyed by an Iskander ballistic missile near Nykanorivka in eastern Ukraine's Donetsk Oblast.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/9k720-iskander] It was the first time a HIMARS system was destroyed in Ukraine.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/9k720-iskander] On 9 March 2024, it was confirmed that an Iskander ballistic missile was used to destroy two German-supplied M901 launchers for the MIM-104 Patriot air defence system near Pokrovsk.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/9k720-iskander] It was the first time components of a Patriot were destroyed in Ukraine.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/9k720-iskander] On 14 March 2024, an Iskander strike destroyed two Ukrainian Mi-8/17 helicopters from the 12th Army Aviation Brigade that were rearming in an open field in Novopavlivka, next to Avdiivka.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/9k720-iskander] On 22 November 2024, another MiG-29 was destroyed in Aviatorskoe-Dnipro air base by an Iskander missiles attack guided by a Russian drone.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/9k720-iskander] On 23 February 2025, the Russian Ministry of Defense claimed that it has hit over 1,400 targets with the Iskander system during the war.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/9k720-iskander] On 1 March 2025, Russian forces attacked a Ukrainian military training site in Cherkaske, leaving scores of Ukrainian soldiers killed and wounded.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/9k720-iskander] On 5 June 2025, Ukrainian military claimed that their missiles struck a base in the city of Klintsy Bryansk Oblast, destroying one Iskander missile launcher and damaged two more.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/9k720-iskander] According to a report by the US Defense Intelligence Agency, Russia upgraded 9K720 Iskander and Kh-47M2 Kinzhal missiles with a terminal phase maneuvering capability in spring 2025 in order to bypass Ukraine's Patriot systems.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/9k720-iskander] According to the French Army, Ukrainian SAMP/T air defence systems have outperformed Patriot missiles in intercepting Iskander missile, after Russia modified the flight profiles of Iskanders.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/9k720-iskander] On 14 March 2026, Ukrainian drones destroyed an Iskander ballistic missile launcher close to the village of Vyshneve in Crimea.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/9k720-iskander] On 17 September 2009, US president Barack Obama announced the cancellation of the U.S. missile defense project in Poland and the Czech Republic.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/9k720-iskander] The following day, Moscow indicated it might in turn cancel the plans to deploy Iskander missiles to Kaliningrad; a few days later, the decision not to deploy was confirmed by Medvedev.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/9k720-iskander] According to Russian unofficial media reports, Russia deployed Iskander missiles to the Kaliningrad Oblast as part of military exercises in March 2015.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/9k720-iskander] On 8 October 2016, the Russian military confirmed that they had moved Iskander-M missiles into the Kaliningrad Oblast, adding the move was part of routine drills and had happened previously multiple times and would happen in future.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/9k720-iskander] In early February 2018, Shamanov confirmed that Russia had deployed an unidentified number of Iskander missiles to the Kaliningrad region.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/9k720-iskander] Days prior, the local military commanders said that the "park zones" for Iskander missiles deployment had been completed in the Kaliningrad region, as well as in North Ossetia.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/9k720-iskander] Armenia reportedly used its Iskander missiles against Azerbaijani forces during the 2020 Nagorno-Karabakh War.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/9k720-iskander] According to unconfirmed claims by ex-president of Armenia Serzh Sargsyan, the missiles were fired on the town of Shushi after its capture by Azerbaijani forces in the last days of the war.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/9k720-iskander] The Russian Ministry of Defence released a statement claiming that the Iskander missiles were not used at all during the 2020 Nagorno-Karabakh War.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/9k720-iskander] Another claim was made by an anonymous Azerbaijani official that Armenian forces fired an Iskander missile at Azerbaijan's capital Baku in the last days of the 2020 Nagorno-Karabakh War, but it was shot down by an Israeli-made Barak 8.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/9k720-iskander] On 15 March, employees of the Azerbaijan National Agency for Mine Action, who were demining and clearing the territories from mines and shells in Shushi, discovered the wreckage of an Iskander-M missile with identification number 9M723.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-54-phoenix] The **AIM-54 Phoenix** is an American active radar-guided, beyond-visual-range air-to-air missile (AAM), carried in clusters of up to six missiles on the Grumman F-14 Tomcat, its only operational launch platform.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-54-phoenix] The combination of Phoenix missile and the Tomcat's AN/AWG-9 guidance radar meant that it was the first aerial weapons system that could simultaneously engage multiple targets.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-54-phoenix] Due to its active radar tracking, the brevity code "Fox Three" was used when firing the AIM-54.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-54-phoenix] The act of the missile achieving a radar lock with its own radar is known under brevity as "Going Pitbull".
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-54-phoenix] Both the missile and the aircraft were used by Iran and the United States Navy (USN).
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-54-phoenix] In US service both are now retired, the AIM-54 Phoenix in 2004 and the F-14 in 2006.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-54-phoenix] They were replaced by the shorter-range AIM-120 AMRAAM, employed on the F/A-18 Hornet and F/A-18E/F Super Hornet; in its AIM-120D version, the latest version of the AMRAAM just matches the Phoenix's maximum range.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-54-phoenix] In July 2024, the USN announced the operational fielding of the AIM-174, the "Air-Launched Configuration" of the RIM-174 Standard ERAM, the first dedicated long-range AAM to be fielded by the U.S. military since the AIM-54's retirement.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-54-phoenix] The AIM-54 has been used in 62 air-to-air kills, all by Iran during the eight-year Iran–Iraq War.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-54-phoenix] Following the retirement of the F-14 by the USN, the weapon's only current operator is the Islamic Republic of Iran Air Force.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-54-phoenix] Since 1951, the Navy faced the initial threat from the Tupolev Tu-4K "Bull" carrying anti-ship missiles or nuclear bombs.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-54-phoenix] Eventually, during the height of the Cold War, the threat would have expanded into regimental-size raids of Tu-16 "Badger" and Tu-22M "Backfire" bombers equipped with low-flying, long-range, high-speed, nuclear-armed cruise missiles and considerable electronic countermeasures (ECM) of various types.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-54-phoenix] This combination was considered capable of saturating fleet defenses and threatening carrier groups.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-54-phoenix] The Navy would require a long-range, long-endurance interceptor aircraft to defend carrier battle groups against this threat.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-54-phoenix] The proposed Douglas F6D Missileer was intended to fulfill this mission and oppose the attack as far as possible from the fleet it was defending.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-54-phoenix] The weapon needed for interceptor aircraft, the Bendix AAM-N-10 Eagle, was to be an air-to-air missile of unprecedented range when compared to contemporary AIM-7 Sparrow missiles.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-54-phoenix] It would work together with Westinghouse AN/APQ-81 radar.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-54-phoenix] The Missileer project was cancelled in December 1960.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-54-phoenix] Navy made the next interceptor attempt with the F-111B, and they needed a new missile design.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-54-phoenix] At the same time, the USAF canceled the projects for their land-based high-speed interceptor aircraft, the North American XF-108 Rapier and the Lockheed YF-12, and left the capable AIM-47 Falcon missile at a quite advanced stage of development, but with no effective launch platform.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-54-phoenix] Originally designated **AAM-N-11**, the AIM-54 Phoenix, developed for the F-111B fleet air defense fighter, had an airframe with four cruciform fins that was a scaled-up version of the AIM-47.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-54-phoenix] One characteristic of the Missileer ancestry was that the radar sent it mid-course corrections, which allowed the fire control system to "loft" the missile up over the target into thinner air where it had better range.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-54-phoenix] Its weapons system, the AIM-54 working with the AWG-9 radar, migrated to the new U.S.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-54-phoenix] Navy fighter project, the VFX, which would later become the F-14 Tomcat.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-54-phoenix] The AIM-54 Phoenix was also considered by the Royal Air Force to be used on Avro Vulcan bomber planes as part of an air defence aircraft.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-54-phoenix] This missileer conversion would have used 12 missiles onboard and an extensive modification to the Vulcan's radar.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-54-phoenix] In 1977, development of a significantly improved Phoenix version, the AIM-54C, was developed to better counter projected threats from tactical anti-naval aircraft and cruise missiles, and its final upgrade included a re-programmable memory capability to keep pace with emerging ECM.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-54-phoenix] The AIM-54/AWG-9 combination had multiple track (up to 24 targets) and multiple launch (up to six Phoenixes can be launched nearly simultaneously) capability, regardless of weather conditions or heavy enemy electronic warfare, known as jamming.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-54-phoenix] The large 1,000 lb (500 kg) missile is equipped with a conventional warhead.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-54-phoenix] The AIM-54 is designed for ejection launch, where a pyrotechnic charge forcefully jettisons it from either a LAU-93 or a LAU-132 launcher before its solid propellant rocket motor ignites.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-54-phoenix] On the F-14, four missiles can be carried under the fuselage tunnel attached to special aerodynamic pallets, plus two under glove stations.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-54-phoenix] A full load of six Phoenix missiles and the unique launch rails weighs in at over 8,000 lb (3,600 kg), about twice the weight of Sparrows, putting it above the allowable bringback load (which also would include enough fuel for go-around attempts).
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-54-phoenix] As such, carrying six Phoenix missiles would necessitate the jettison of at least some of the Phoenix missiles if they were not used.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-54-phoenix] The most common air superiority payload was a mix of two Phoenix, three Sparrow, and two Sidewinder missiles.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-54-phoenix] Most other US aircraft relied on the smaller, semi-active medium-range AIM-7 Sparrow.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-54-phoenix] Semi-active guidance meant the aircraft no longer had a search capability while supporting the launched Sparrow, reducing situational awareness.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-54-phoenix] The Tomcat's radar could track up to 24 targets in track-while-scan mode, with the AWG-9 selecting up to six potential targets for the missiles.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-54-phoenix] The pilot or radar intercept officer (RIO) could then launch the Phoenix missiles once parameters were met.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-54-phoenix] The Link 4 datalink allowed US Navy Tomcats to share information with the E-2C Hawkeye AEW aircraft.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-54-phoenix] During Desert Shield in 1990, the Link 4A was introduced; this allowed the Tomcats to have a fighter-to-fighter datalink capability, further enhancing overall situational awareness.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-54-phoenix] The F-14D entered service with JTIDS that brought the even better Link 16 datalink "picture" to the cockpit.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-54-phoenix] The Phoenix has several guidance modes and achieves its longest range by using mid-course updates from the F-14A/B AWG-9 radar (APG-71 radar in the F-14D) as it climbs to cruise between 80,000 ft (24,000 m) and 100,000 ft (30,000 m) at close to Mach 5.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-54-phoenix] The Phoenix uses this high altitude to maximize its range by reducing atmospheric drag.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-54-phoenix] At around 11 miles (18 km) from the target, the missile activates its own radar to provide terminal guidance.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-54-phoenix] Minimum engagement range for the Phoenix is around 2 nmi (3.7 km); at this range active homing would initiate upon launch.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-54-phoenix] If the AWG-9 radar lost radar lock on a target before the missile had activated its own radar, the missile proceeded on a ballistic trajectory with no further guidance, known as 'going dumb'.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-54-phoenix] The AIM-54 Phoenix was retired from USN service on September 30, 2004.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-54-phoenix] F-14 Tomcats were retired on September 22, 2006.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-54-phoenix] They were replaced by shorter-range AIM-120 AMRAAMs, employed on the F/A-18E/F Super Hornet.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-54-phoenix] Despite the much-vaunted capabilities, the Phoenix was rarely used in combat, with only two confirmed launches and no confirmed targets destroyed in US Navy service.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-54-phoenix] The USAF F-15 Eagle had responsibility for overland combat air patrol duties in Operation Desert Storm in 1991, primarily because of the onboard F-15 IFF capabilities.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-54-phoenix] The Tomcat did not have the requisite IFF capability mandated by the Joint Force Air Component Commander (JFACC) to satisfy the rules of engagement to utilize the Phoenix capability at beyond visual range.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-54-phoenix] The AIM-54 was not adopted by any foreign nation besides Iran, or any other US armed service, and was not used on any aircraft other than the F-14.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-54-phoenix] On January 7, 1974, as part of Project *Persian King*, the Imperial Iranian Air Force placed an order for 424 AIM-54As, later increasing it by 290 missiles that June.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-54-phoenix] Of the initial order, 274 missiles and 10 training rounds were delivered for US$150 million, until the 1979 Revolution ended deliveries and left the remaining 150 missiles embargoed and the additional order of 290 cancelled.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-54-phoenix] According to Tom Cooper and Farzad Bishop, during the Iran–Iraq War AIM-54s fired by IRIAF Tomcats achieved 78 victories against Iraqi MiG-21s, MiG-23s, MiG-25s, Tu-22s, Su-20/22s, Mirage F1s, Super Étendards, and even two AM-39 Exocets and a C-601.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-54-phoenix] This includes two occasions where one AIM-54 was responsible for the downing of two Iraqi aircraft, as well as an incident on January 7, 1981, where a Phoenix fired at a four-ship of MiG-23BNs downed three and damaged the fourth.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-54-phoenix] The US refused to supply spare parts and maintenance after the 1979 Revolution, except for a brief period during the Iran–Contra affair.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-54-phoenix] According to Cooper, the Islamic Republic of Iran Air Force kept its F-14 fighters and AIM-54 missiles in regular use during the entire Iran–Iraq War, though periodic lack of spares grounded large parts of the fleet at times.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-54-phoenix] During late 1987, the stock of AIM-54 missiles was at its lowest, with fewer than 50 operational missiles available.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-54-phoenix] The missiles needed fresh thermal batteries that could only be purchased from the US.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-54-phoenix] Iran found a clandestine buyer that supplied it with batteries, which cost up to US$10,000 each.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-54-phoenix] Iran received spares and parts for both the F-14s and AIM-54s from various sources during the Iran–Iraq War, and has received more spares after the conflict.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-54-phoenix] Iran started a program to build spares for the planes and missiles, and although there are claims that it no longer relies on outside sources to keep its F-14s and AIM-54s operational, there is evidence that Iran continues to procure parts clandestinely.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-54-phoenix] Both the F-14 Tomcat and the AIM-54 Phoenix missile continue in the service of the Islamic Republic of Iran Air Force.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-54-phoenix] In 2013, Iran unveiled the Fakour-90, a missile that is thought to be developed from the Phoenix and the MIM-23 Hawk surface-to-air missile.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-54-phoenix] A version with simplified construction and no coolant conditioning.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-54-phoenix] Developmental work started in January 1972.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-54-phoenix] 7 X-AIM-54B missiles were created for testing, 6 of them by modifying pilot production IVE/PIP rounds.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-54-phoenix] After two successful test firings, the 'Dry' missile effort was cancelled for being "not cost effective".
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-54-phoenix] The only improved model that was ever produced.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-54-phoenix] in the place of the analog electronics of the AIM-54A.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-54-phoenix] It was designed for greater service life, reliability, and utilized less parts.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-54-phoenix] (BIST/BIT) and missile on-aircraft test capability.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-54-phoenix] This model took over from the AIM-54A beginning in 1986.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-54-phoenix] It did not require coolant during flight.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-54-phoenix] The missile was deployed from 1988 onwards.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-54-phoenix] Because the AIM-54 ECCM/Sealed received no coolant, F-14s carrying this version of the missile could not exceed a specified airspeed.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-54-phoenix] There were also test, evaluation, ground training, and captive air training versions of the missile; designated ATM-54, AEM-54, DATM-54A, and CATM-54, respectively.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-54-phoenix] The flight versions had A and C versions.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-54-phoenix] The DATM-54 was not made in a C version as there was no change in the ground handling characteristics.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-54-phoenix] A small number of AIM-54As were also converted to NAIM-54As, carrying scientific recording equipment; their use is unknown.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-54-phoenix] Hughes Aircraft touted the fact that 27 out of 29 major elements of the standard (airborne) AN/AWG-9 could be used in the shipborne version with little modification.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-54-phoenix] Each system would have consisted of one AWG-9 radar, with associated controls and displays, and a fixed 12-cell launcher for the Phoenix missiles.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-54-phoenix] In the case of an aircraft carrier, for example, at least three systems would have been fitted in order to give overlapping coverage throughout the full 360°.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-54-phoenix] The AWG‑9’s track‑while‑scan capability could monitor up to 24 targets simultaneously; however, on the Tomcat, engagements were limited to 6 targets per launching aircraft, as this was the maximum number of Phoenixes a single Tomcat could carry.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-54-phoenix] With the potential for greater "magazine depth" abord ships, the Sea Phoenix would be possibly capable of engaging up to 24 targets simultaneously per AN/AWG-9 system.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-54-phoenix] in 1974 where it successfully detected and tracked multiple high‑ and low‑altitude targets from the ship’s deck; unconfirmed reports also describe a "containerised" AWG‑9 trial at Point Mugu as a possible land‑based mobile testbed.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-54-phoenix] Development of the land- and sea-based versions did not proceed largely because of high cost and the reduced range and performance penalty of surface launch relative to airborne launch.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-54-phoenix] The AN/AWG‑9’s limited ability to track low‑altitude targets when ship‑mounted was also noted in tests.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-54-phoenix] Redundancy was also noted, with contemporary fleet defense being provided predominantly by F-14s, themselves already equipped with the AWG‑9/AIM‑54 suite.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-54-phoenix] and upgraded Sea Sparrow variants becoming operational, any further development of the Sea Phoenix was halted.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-54-phoenix] regarding these shortcomings and advised that testing found the Sea Phoenix to be "not favorable" and that it offered "no advantages" over Aegis and Sea Sparrow systems.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-54-phoenix] In February 2013 Iran reportedly tested an indigenous long-range air-to-air missile.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-54-phoenix] It looked almost identical to the AIM-54 Phoenix.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-54-phoenix] In July 2018 as reported by Jane's, Iran started mass production of the Fakour-90.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] The **AIM-9 Sidewinder** is a short-range air-to-air missile.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] It entered service with the United States Navy in 1956 and the Air Force in 1964, and is one of the oldest, cheapest, and most successful air-to-air missiles.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] Its latest variants (AIM-9X) remain standard equipment in most Western-aligned air forces.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] The Soviet K-13 (AA-2 "Atoll"), a reverse-engineered copy of the AIM-9B, was also widely adopted.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] Low-level development started in the late 1940s, emerging in the early 1950s as a guidance system for the modular Zuni rocket.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] This modularity allowed for the introduction of newer seekers and rocket motors, including the AIM-9C variant, which used semi-active radar homing and served as the basis of the AGM-122 Sidearm anti-radar missile.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] Due to the Sidewinder's infrared guidance system, the brevity code "Fox two" is used when firing the AIM-9.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] Originally a tail-chasing system, early models saw extensive use during the Vietnam War, but had a low success rate (8% hit rate with the AIM-9E variant).
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] This led to all-aspect capability in the L (Lima) version, which proved an effective weapon during the 1982 Falklands War and Operation Mole Cricket 19 in Lebanon.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] Its adaptability has kept it in service over newer designs like the AIM-95 Agile and SRAAM that were intended to replace it.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] The Sidewinder is the most widely used air-to-air missile in the West, with more than 110,000 missiles produced for the U.S. and 27 other nations, of which perhaps one percent have been used in combat.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] It has been built under license by Sweden and other nations.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] The AIM-9 has an estimated 270 aircraft kills.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] In 2010, Boeing won a contract to support Sidewinder operations through to 2055.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] In 2021 an Air Force spokesperson said that its relatively low cost, versatility, and reliability mean it is "very possible that the Sidewinder will remain in Air Force inventories through the late 21st century".
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] The AIM-9 was a product of the US Naval Weapons Center at China Lake in the Mojave Desert.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] It features a lightweight, compact design with cruciform canards and tail fins.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] It uses a solid rocket motor for propulsion, similar to most conventional missiles, a continuous-rod fragmentation warhead, and an infrared seeker.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] The seeker tracks a difference in temperatures detected and uses proportional guidance to achieve impact.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] Older variants such as the AIM-9B with uncooled seeker heads could track only the high temperatures of engine exhaust, making them strictly rear-aspect.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] Later variants, however, featured liquid nitrogen coolant bottles in the launchers, allowing the missile to track any part of the aircraft heated by air resistance due to high-speed flight, giving modern Sidewinders all-aspect capabilities.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] The nose canards provide maneuverability for the AIM-9, with the AIM-9X using thrust vectoring to augment this.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] The hot gases generated were used to actuate the nose canards in older models, while newer variants use thermal batteries.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] To minimize the amount of energy devoted to actuating control surfaces, the AIM-9 does not use active roll stabilization.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] Instead, it uses rollerons, small finned metal discs protruding out of the aft end of the tips of the tail fins which are spun by the passing airflow as the missile flies through the air, providing gyroscopic stabilization.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] The AIM-9 uses a passive infrared proximity fuze to detonate its warhead near an enemy aircraft, scattering fragments that aim to damage the aircraft, rendering it inoperable.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] The continuous rod warhead features rods welded together to form a cylindrical outer shell, with explosive filler inside.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] Upon detonation, the rods expand in a toroidal shape, ensuring that at least some portion of the shrapnel hits enemy aircraft.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] Newer models of the AIM-9 sought to increase the range that the seeker head's gimbal can turn, allowing the missile to track aircraft at greater angles from its direct line of sight, or boresight.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] Models such as the AIM-9L, AIM-9M, and AIM-9X feature high off-boresight capabilities, meaning they are able to track targets at high seeker gimbal angles, or highly distant from the boresight.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] The Sidewinder is guided not by the actual position recorded by the detector, but by the *change* in position since the last sighting.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] So if the target remains at 5 degrees left between two rotations of the mirror, the electronics would not output any signal to the control system.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] Consider a missile fired at right angles to its target; if the missile is flying at the same speed as the target, it should "lead" it by 45 degrees, flying to an impact point far in front of where the target was when it was fired.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] If the missile is traveling four times the speed of the target, it should follow an angle about 11 degrees in front.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] In either case, the missile should keep that angle all the way to interception, which means that the angle that the target makes against the detector is constant.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] It was this constant angle that the Sidewinder attempted to maintain.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] This "proportional pursuit" system is straightforward to implement and offers high-performance lead calculation almost for free and can respond to changes in the target's flight path, which is much more efficient and makes the missile "lead" the target.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] During World War II, various researchers in Germany designed infrared guidance systems of various complexity.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] The most mature development of these, codenamed *Hamburg*, was intended for use by the Blohm & Voss BV 143 glide bomb in an anti-ship role.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] *Hamburg* used a single IR photocell as its detector along with a spinning disk with lines painted on it, alternately known as a "reticle" or "chopper".
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] The reticle spun at a fixed speed, causing the output of the photocell to be interrupted in a pattern, and the precise timing of the resulting signal indicated the bearing of the target.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] Although *Hamburg* and similar devices like *Madrid* were essentially complete, the work of mating them to a missile had not been carried out by the time the war ended.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] In the immediate post-war era, Allied military intelligence teams collected this information, along with many of the engineers working on these projects.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] Several lengthy reports on the various systems were produced and disseminated among the Western aircraft firms, while a number of the engineers joined these companies to work on various missile projects.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] By the late 1940s a wide variety of missile projects were underway, from huge systems like the Bell Bomi rocket-powered bomber to small systems like air-to-air missiles.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] By the early 1950s, both the US Air Force and Royal Air Force had started major IR seeker missile projects.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] The development of the Sidewinder missile began in 1946 at the Naval Ordnance Test Station (NOTS), Inyokern, California, now the Naval Air Weapons Station China Lake, as an in-house research project conceived by William B.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] McLean initially called his effort "Local Fuze Project 602" using laboratory funding, volunteer help and fuze funding to develop what they called a heat-homing rocket.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] The name *Sidewinder* was selected in 1950 and is the common name of *Crotalus cerastes*, a rattlesnake, which uses infrared sensory organs to hunt warm-blooded prey.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] It did not receive official funding until 1951 when the effort was mature enough to show to Admiral William "Deak" Parsons, the Deputy Chief of the Bureau of Ordnance (BuOrd).
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] It subsequently received designation as a program in 1952.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] Originally called the **Sidewinder 1**, the first live firing was on 3 September 1952.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] The missile intercepted a drone for the first time on 11 September 1953.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] The missile carried out 51 guided flights in 1954, and in 1955 production was authorized.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] In 1954, the US Air Force carried out trials with the original **AIM-9A** and the improved **AIM-9B** at the Holloman Air Development Center.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] The first operational use of the missile was by Grumman F9F-8 Cougars and FJ-3 Furies of the United States Navy in the middle of 1956.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] Nearly 100,000 of the first generation (AIM-9B/C/D/E) of the Sidewinder were produced with Raytheon and General Electric as major subcontractors.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] Philco-Ford produced the guidance and control sections of the early missiles.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] The NATO version of the first-generation missile was built under license in Germany by Bodenseewerk Gerätetechnik; 9,200 examples were built.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] The AIM-9A and AIM-9B were originally fitted with a non-propulsive attachment (NPA) for their MK 15 and MK 17 rocket motors.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] If the motor accidentally ignited while kept in storage, during transport, or while it was fitted to the aircraft hardpoints, the NPA would direct the exhaust gases at right angles rather than straight back.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] In these cases, the missile would not move.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] While the NPA safety device itself suffered no failures, some ordnance men forgot to remove them after hanging the missiles in the hardpoints.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] When the pilots attempted to fire the missiles in flight, the hot exhaust gases were redirected directly towards the wings, severely damaging the aircraft.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] After losing three aircraft in this manner, the US Navy withdrew the NPA from use.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] The AIM-9B is very similar to the AIM-9A, but the "B" has a more sophisticated rear and more aerodynamical front fins.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] The AIM-9B is a very limited weapon, but it had no serious competitors and counters when it was introduced, causing it to be adopted by the USAF and NATO as a standard weapon, with around 80,000 units being produced from 1958 to 1962.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] The viewing angle of the AIM-9B's sensor was a minuscule 4 degrees, so at launch, the pilot had to accurately aim the aircraft's sight over or above the target (to account for drag).
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] The speed of the conical scan was very slow, additionally, the uncooled missile had a low sensitivity and was liable to extraneous heat.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] The AIM-9B was recommended for use on non-threatening targets (like bombers), only from behind (so it can lock on the thermal radiation from the target engines) and only with the sun behind or to the side of the launching aircraft (as the missile would lock onto it due to its thermal radiation).
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] It was famously the first Sidewinder variant to be fired in anger as on 24 September 1958, it achieved the world's first successful kill with an air-to-air missile, when Taiwanese F-86Fs shot down Communist Chinese MiG-15s using AIM-9Bs supplied and fitted by the U.S.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] The K-13/R-3 was reverse-engineered from the American AIM-9B Sidewinder.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] During the Taiwan Strait conflict in 1958, an AIM-9B Sidewinder missile fell near Wenzhou without exploding and was recovered by Chinese forces.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] The Soviets later learned that the Chinese had obtained the missile, and after negotiations, they persuaded the Chinese to send one to the Soviet Union, which enabled them to develop the K-13.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] The lackluster performance of the AIM-9B caused the Navy to look for a successor.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] In 1963 the AAM-N-7 *Sidewinder IC* was developed in two variations: a SARH (semi-active radar homing) variant (AIM-9C) and an IR (AIM-9D) in 1963.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] The AIM-9C's semi-active radar was exclusively tied to the F-8 Crusader's radar and fire control system (FCS).
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] A total of around 1,000 AIM-9C missiles were launched from 1965 to 1967, but their usage in the Vietnam war proved unsuccessful, downing no enemies.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] A filter modification program for reworked units (to allow high altitude capability up to 18,288m (60,000 feet)) was the only planned modification.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] Recognizing the limitations of the initial AIM-9B, the US Navy (USN) worked to improve the missile's performance.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] They changed the missile nose to an aerodynamical ogival nose.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] The seeker was improved with a wider field of view beyond 25 degrees and a reduced instantaneous field of view of 2.5 degrees to reduce foreign thermal interference (primarily from flares).
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] A nitrogen cooling system was added for the fuze, enhancing the missile's heat sensitivity.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] Maneuverability was also improved with a faster tracking rate and a new actuator system.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] The Sidewinder's range was improved as well, with the new Hercules MK 36 solid-fuel rocket motor allowing the missile to fly up to 18 km.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] Finally, a new Mk 48 continuous-rod warhead was fitted to the missile for increased damage; this also meant infrared or a radio proximity fuze could be used.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] These improvements were all added to the AIM-9D and went into service with the USN.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] Around 1,000 AIM-9D units were produced from 1965 to 1969.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] A significant issue with the AIM-9D was breakup during launch.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] The AIM-9D was eventually developed into the AIM-9G.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] The AIM-9E "Echo" was the first version developed solely by the U.S.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] The AIM-9E allows the expansion of the weapons acquisition envelope, especially at low-altitude, increasing its Probability of Kill (P[k]).
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] It achieved this using a new low-drag conical nose head, being a distinguishing feature of USAF Sidewinders.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] A magnesium fluoride seeker dome was introduced, along with a more compact optical assembly, an improved guidance control system, new electronics, and significant changes to the internal wiring harnesses.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] These improvements facilitated a better 100 Hz reticle rate, and a 16.5 deg/sec tracking rate.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] The most significant design change was the addition of cooling for the PbS detector, adding Peltier (thermoelectric) cooling, giving the advantage of unlimited cooling when positioned on the launch rail, but is only active when electrical power is present.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] The AIM-9E gives greater range over the AIM-9B, but is worse than the "D".
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] Over 5,000 AIM-9B's were rebuilt into AIM-9E's.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] The AIM-9E appeared in Vietnam after the conclusion of the Operation Rolling Thunder in 1968, with the U.S.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] Air Force (USAF), becoming one of their main missile armaments.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] Up until Operation Linebacker in 1972 intense air-to-air activity in Vietnam was not present.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] There were 71 AIM-9E launch attempts from January to October 1972, however, only 6 missiles managed to down an aircraft, with 1 other hitting an aircraft, but not causing complete destruction.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] Reasons for the poor success rate was listed as "poor air crew training, launches out of the envelope, the tactical situation, marginal tone, tone discrimination, the missile going ballistic, and other malfunctions".
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] As the Sidewinder was being acquired by NATO forces, licensed production was given to West Germany and they would produce around 15,000 units.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] Like the Americans, the West Germans sought to improve the AIM-9B design due to its limitations.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] The only visible exterior difference is a greenish sensor window, but many tech improvements were added beneath the shell.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] Unnoticed improvements include solid state electronics (instead of vacuum tubes), carbon dioxide seeker cooling, a new nose dome and superior optical filtering.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] Conversions were done to European AIM-9Bs to upgrade them to the FGW.2 standard.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] The official designation is the AIM-9B FGW.2 but it is known as the AIM-9F in US nomenclature.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] The AIM-9G was very similar to the AIM-9D in most aspects, and did not differ externally.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] This was connected to the onboard computer of the aircraft, which gave the capability of capturing the target using the data coming from the airborne radar.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] This meant that the target could be locked without being in the sights, and the missile automatically got pre-launch instructions.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] The conical scanning speed was also increased greatly.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] The seeker head was now able to seek in a 25˚ circular scan.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] This allowed the AIM-9G to have an improved chance of acquiring the target than earlier models.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] This, along with other upgraded solid-state modules, culminated in the AIM-9G.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] The improvement was substantial enough that an order of 5,000 AIM-9D seekers was stopped at 1,850 units, with the rest being ordered to AIM-9G seeker specifications instead.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] Around 2120 AIM-9G were built by Raytheon from 1970 to 1972.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] The AIM-9G would be used with its predecessor, the AIM-9D, during the Vietnam War, as the US Navy's choice of IR missile.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] A 46% hit rate with the AIM-9G during Operation Linebackers I and II in 1972 was achieved, of which 14 aircraft were MiG-17s and the other 7 were MiG-21s.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] This was due to the missile design and USN fighter pilot training at TOPGUN.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] The United States Air Force attempted to attain AIM-9Gs from the USN, due to bad experience with their AIM-9 Sidewinders models (B, E, and J), but they were incompatible with US Air Force's Sidewinder launchers due to the different cooling mechanisms.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] Within December 1965, two designers McLean and LaBerge (who were employed by Philco-Ford) came together to create ways to improve the AIM-9G's reliability.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] One submission was to advance all the remaining missile electronic components from vacuum to solid-state gradually.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] The US Air Force adhered to this steady replacement of their AIM-9s to solid-state, however the Navy opted for a different approach after Walt Freitag, a USN engineer proposed a full change to solid-state in one missile.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] The "H" variant had major changes over the AIM-9D/G, which had multiple issues with reliability.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] One of the issues was the intolerance of the vacuum tubes to repeated 20 ft/sec sink rate landings by US Navy aircraft on carrier decks.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] The "H" was the first Sidewinder to be fully solid state, replacing the original vacuum tubes.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] The AIM-9H also included a new lead sulphide detector, using nitrogen cooling.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] The new guidance package was built using semiconductors.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] When the engineers redesigned these electronics, they essentially kept the AIM-9G's optical system, but the tracking rate increased further, from the original 12˚ to 20˚ degrees per second, this complementing the more powerful 120 lb.ft actuators that had been installed.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] They also replaced the thermal battery with a turbo-alternator.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] The AIM-9H also included a continuous-rod bundle warhead, improving its destructive capability.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] The AIM-9H was the last and most maneuverable of the rear-aspect USN Sidewinders, with USN moving to the all-aspect AIM-9L.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] The AIM-9H was actually used at the very end of the Vietnam war, with it being introduced into the US navy service in 1972 and being used in Operation Linebacker.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] A total of around 7,700 AIM-9H units would be manufactured from 1972 to 1974 by Philco-Ford and Raytheon.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] The AIM-9H was the basis for the all-aspect USAF/USN AIM-9L.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] Navy (USN) upgrade to the AIM-9H, but the development was abandoned in favor of USAF/USN joint AIM-9L.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] As the AIM-9E Sidewinder was entering service in Southeast Asia during the conclusion of Operation Rolling Thunder, the USAF started the development the next generation Sidewinders to replace the AIM-9E.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] In November 1968, the testing of an AIM-9E upgrade the "Extended Performance" began.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] The missile was designed to give pilots a more capable close-range IR missile against a maneuvering target.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] It would eventually be designated the AIM-9J.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] Preliminary testing of the AIM-9J ended on 3 July 1972, indicating that further in-depth testing and evaluation were necessary prior to replacing the AIM-9B/E.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] On 8 June 1972, the AIM-9J was authorized for introduction into Southeast Asia under Phase IIA of its evaluation program, and approval to employ it in combat was received on 31 July 1972.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] The first combat flight of the AIM-9J occurred on 2 August 1972, but it wasn't until 9 September 1972 that the first three AIM-9Js were fired in combat.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] Only 31 combat firings were attempted before the cease fire in January, 1973.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] Considering the original intent of its development, the AIM-9J performance was relatively unimpressive in combat.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] Nevertheless, compared to its competitors (the AIM-7E-2 and the AIM-9E), the AIM-9J did appear relatively successful.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] The AIM-9J kill rate per missile fired was 13 percent from September to December 1972, compared to 5 percent and 8 percent registered by the AIM-7E-2 and AIM-9E, respectively.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] When viewed on the basis of effectiveness per engagement, the AIM-9J fared better with 33 percent kills per engagement, versus 11 percent and 15 percent for the AIM-7E-2 and AIM-9E, respectively.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] The AIM-9J was an upgrade to the AIM-9E.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] Around 6,700 AIM-9Js were built from 1972 onward.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] These were mostly converted existing AIM-9B/E missiles.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] The AIM-9P Sidewinder missile was a USAF sponsored family of export missiles based on the AIM-9J/N, and would be upgraded multiple times over its lifespan.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] The AIM-9P was an improved AIM-9J with a new motor, fuze and better reliability.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] It included a greater engagement range, allowing it to be launched farther from the target.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] The AIM-9P was more maneuverable than the AIM-9J, and also included improved solid-state electronics that increased reliability and maintainability.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] The AIM-9P was either a rebuilt B/E or J or all-new production.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] Note: the speed of the B model was around 1.7 Mach and the other models above 2.5.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] The next major advance in IR Sidewinder development was the **AIM-9L** (**"Lima"**) model which was in full production in 1977.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] This was the first "all-aspect" Sidewinder with the ability to attack from all directions, including head-on, which had a dramatic effect on close-in combat tactics.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] Its first combat use was by a pair of US Navy F-14s in the Gulf of Sidra in 1981 versus two Libyan Sukhoi Su-22s, both of the latter being destroyed by AIM-9Ls.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] Its first use in a large-scale conflict was by the United Kingdom during the 1982 Falklands War.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] In this campaign the "Lima" reportedly achieved kills from 80% of launches, a dramatic improvement over the 10–15% levels of earlier versions, scoring 17 kills and 2 shared kills against Argentine aircraft.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] The **AIM-9M** is an improved AIM-9L inheriting the all-aspect capability of the L model, but providing all-around higher performance.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] Having a better background rejection and infrared countermeasures discrimination (WGU-4/B), a low-smoke motor to reduce the visual signature of the weapon, and improved guidance control section with counter-countermeasures and improved maintainability and producibility.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] The AIM-9M uses an annular blast fragmentation warhead.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] These modifications increase ability to locate and lock-on a target and decrease the missile's chances for detection.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] It was deployed in large numbers during the 1991 Gulf War, the AIM-9M was responsible for all 10 Sidewinder kills recorded during that conflict.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] The AIM-9M was used by the RAAF's being their standard dogfight AAM, carried by the F/A-18 and F-111.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] The first live firing occurred in 1990, but in 1992, production was cancelled as a lack of funding due to defense budget cuts.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] The AIM-9S is a modified AIM-9M with the counter-countermeasures (CCM) equipment removed from the guidance-control section.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] This derivative is used for FMS (Foreign Military Sales), giving the latest Sidewinder technology to US allies without giving away valuable missile technology.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] A customer of the AIM-9S was Turkey with them having 310 units in 2005.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] China Lake developed an improved compressed carriage control configuration titled BOA.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] "Compressed carriage" missiles have smaller control surfaces to allow more missiles to fit in a given space.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] The surfaces may be permanently "clipped", or may fold out when the missile is launched.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] Hughes Electronics was awarded a contract for development of the **AIM-9X** Sidewinder in 1996 after a competition against Raytheon for the next short-range aerial combat missile, though Raytheon purchased the defense portions of Hughes Electronics the following year.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] Joint Helmet Mounted Cueing System (JHMCS), and a totally new two-axis thrust-vectoring control (TVC) system providing increased turn capability over traditional control surfaces (60 *g*).
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] Using the JHMCS, a pilot can point the AIM-9X missile's seeker and "lock on" by simply looking at a target, thereby increasing air combat effectiveness.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] It retains the same rocket motor, fuze and warhead of the AIM-9M, but its lower drag gives it improved range and speed.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] The AIM-9X also includes an internal cooling system, eliminating the need to use launch-rail nitrogen bottles (U.S.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] Navy and Marines) or internal argon bottles (USAF).
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] It also features an electronic safe and arm device similar to the AMRAAM, allowing for a reduction in minimum range, and reprogrammable infrared Counter Counter Measures (IRCCM) capability that coupled with the FPA provides improved look down into clutter and performance against the latest IRCM.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] Though not part of the original requirement, the AIM-9X demonstrated potential for lock-on after launch capability, allowing for possible internal use for the F-35 Lightning II, F-22 Raptor and even in a submarine-launched configuration for use against ASW platforms.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] The AIM-9X has been tested for a surface attack capability, with mixed results.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] Testing work on the AIM-9X Block II version began in September 2008.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] The Block II adds lock-on after launch capability with a datalink, so the missile can be launched first and then directed to its target afterwards by an aircraft with the proper equipment for 360-degree engagements, such as the F-35 or the F-22.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] By January 2013, the AIM-9X Block II was about halfway through its operational testing and performing better than expected.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] NAVAIR reported that the missile was exceeding performance requirements in all areas, including lock-on after launch (LOAL).
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] One area where the Block II needs improvement is helmetless high off-boresight (HHOBS) performance.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] It is functioning well on the missile, but performance is below that of the Block I AIM-9X.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] The HHOBS deficiency does not impact any other Block II capabilities, and is planned to be improved upon by a software clean-up build.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] Objectives of the operational test were due to be completed by the third quarter of 2013.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] However, as of May 2014 there have been plans to resume operational testing and evaluation (including surface-to-air missile system compatibility).
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] As of June 2013, Raytheon had delivered 5,000 AIM-9X missiles to the armed services.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] On 18 June 2017, after an AIM-9X did not successfully track a targeted Syrian Air Force Su-22 Fitter, US Navy Lt.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] Michael "Mob" Tremel flying a F/A-18E Super Hornet used an AMRAAM AAM to successfully destroy the enemy aircraft.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] There is a theory that the Sidewinder is tested against American and not Soviet/Russian flares.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] The Sidewinder is used to rejecting American but not Soviet/Russian flares.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] Similar issues arose from the testing of the AIM-9P model.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] Army successfully launched an AIM-9X Block II from the new Multi-Mission Launcher (MML), a truck-mounted missile launch container that can hold 15 of the missiles.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] The MML is part of the Indirect Fire Protection Capability Increment 2-Intercept (IFPC Inc.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] 2-I) to protect ground forces against cruise missile and unmanned aerial vehicle threats.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] The AIM-9X Block II has been determined by the Army to be the best solution to cruise missile and UAV threats because of its passive imaging infrared seeker.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] The MML will complement the AN/TWQ-1 Avenger air defense system and is expected to begin fielding in 2019.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] In September 2012, Raytheon was ordered to continue developing the Sidewinder into a Block III variant, even though the Block II had not yet entered service.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] The USN projected that the new missile would have a 60 percent longer range, modern components to replace old ones, and an insensitive munitions warhead, which is more stable and less likely to detonate by accident, making it safer for ground crews.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] The need for the AIM-9 to have an increased range was caused by digital radio frequency memory (DRFM) jammers that can blind the onboard radar of an AIM-120D AMRAAM, so the Sidewinder Block III's passive imaging infrared homing guidance system was seen as a useful alternative.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] Although it could supplement the AMRAAM for beyond visual range (BVR) engagements, it would still be capable of performing within visual range (WVR).
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] Modifying the AIM-9X was seen as a cost-effective alternative to developing a new missile in a time of declining budgets.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] To achieve the range increase, the rocket motor would have a combination of increased performance and missile power management.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] The Block III would "leverage" the Block II's guidance unit and electronics, including the AMRAAM-derived datalink.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] The Block III was scheduled to achieve initial operational capability (IOC) in 2022, following the increased number of F-35 Lightning II Joint Strike Fighters to enter service.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p01] However, the Navy's FY 2016 budget canceled the AIM-9X Block III as they cut down buys of the F-35C, as it was primarily intended to permit the fighter to carry six BVR missiles; the insensitive munition warhead will be retained for the AIM-9X program.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p02] The first combat use of the Sidewinder came on 24 September 1958 by the Republic of China (Taiwan) Air Force during the Second Taiwan Strait Crisis.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p02] At the time, ROCAF North American F-86 Sabres were routinely engaged in air battles with the People's Republic of China over the Taiwan Strait.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p02] In similar fashion to Korean War encounters between the F-86 and earlier MiG-15, high-flying PRC MiG-17s cruised above the ROC Sabres, immune to their .50-cal guns and only fighting when conditions favoured them.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p02] In a highly secret effort, the United States provided a few dozen Sidewinders to ROC forces and an Aviation Ordnance Team from the U.S.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p02] Marine Corps to modify their aircraft to carry the Sidewinder.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p02] In the first encounter on 24 September 1958, ROCAF pilots used the Sidewinders to ambush the MiG-17s as they flew past.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p02] This action marked the first successful use of air-to-air missiles in combat, the downed MiGs being the first casualties.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p02] During the Taiwan Strait battles of 1958, a ROCAF AIM-9B hit a PLAAF MiG-17 without exploding; the missile lodged in the airframe of the MiG and allowed the pilot to bring both plane and missile back to base.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p02] Soviet engineers later said that the captured Sidewinder served as a "university course" in missile design and substantially improved Soviet air-to-air capabilities.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p02] They reverse-engineered a copy of the Sidewinder, which was manufactured as the **Vympel K-13/R-3S** missile, NATO reporting name **AA-2 Atoll**.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p02] The Vympel K-13 entered service with Soviet air forces in 1960.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p02] Performance of the 454 Sidewinders launched during the war was not as satisfactory as hoped.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p02] Both the USN and USAF studied the performance of their aircrews, aircraft, weapons, training, and supporting infrastructure.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p02] The USAF conducted the classified Red Baron Report while the Navy conducted a study concentrating primarily on performance of air-to-air weapons that was informally known as the "Ault Report".
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p02] Both services subsequently modified their AIM-9s to improve performance and reliability.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p02] In total 452 Sidewinders were fired during the Vietnam War, resulting in a kill probability of 18%.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p02] The Services and the Department of Defense were shocked by the poor missile performance - pre-war operational tests predicted that the AIM-9 was expected to hit 65% of the time.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p02] The missile testing program, however, did not reflect how the missiles would be used.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p02] Almost all the tests were against non-maneuvering drone targets at high altitudes, many of them with artificially strengthened radar returns.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p02] The United States Air Force sold the United Kingdom 200 AIM‑9L Sidewinder missiles for use on Harrier aircraft during the Falklands War.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p02] The Royal Navy's Sea Harriers made extensive use of the missile's all‑aspect capability.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p02] Contemporary sources agree that 24 AIM‑9Ls were launched by Sea Harriers operating from *Hermes* and HMS *Invincible*, with 21 striking their targets, giving an overall hit rate of 88 per cent.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p02] Of the three unsuccessful firings, one was launched beyond its seeker's effective range, one suffered a malfunction, and one failed after the target escaped into cloud cover.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p02] Sea Harriers armed with AIM‑9Ls destroyed 19 Argentine aircraft in air‑to‑air combat, including one later shot down by Argentine ground fire after being damaged.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p02] Two of the destroyed aircraft were each hit by two missiles.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p02] The missile's infrared seeker proved especially effective against the hot exhaust of Argentine jets against the cold South Atlantic skies.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p02] On 24 February 1994, three aircraft of the Republika Srpska Air Force were intercepted by USAF F-16s and shot down with Sidewinders after violating the no-fly zone in Bosnia.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p02] On 4 February 2023, an F-22 Raptor operated by the United States Air Force used a single AIM-9X missile to shoot down a suspected Chinese spy balloon off the coast of Surfside Beach, South Carolina at an altitude between 60,000 to 65,000 feet (18,000 to 20,000 m).
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p02] Six days later, another object was shot down near Alaska.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p02] On 11 and 12 February two more objects were shot down, over Yukon, Canada and Lake Huron in Michigan respectively.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p02] On 2 November 2023, Israeli Air Force claimed one of its F-35I have shot down an unidentified cruise missile, using an AIM-9X Sidewinder.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p02] On 3 May 2025, the head of the Ukrainian Main Directorate of Intelligence (HUR), lieutenant general Kyrylo Budanov claimed that three MAGURA V7 naval drones armed with AIM-9 Sidewinders modified for surface-to-air operation shot down two Russian Su-30 fighter jets in the Black Sea.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p02] The Russian Defense Ministry did not comment, but Russian sources report that the pilots of one fighter were rescued by a cargo ship, whose crew received an award.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p02] On September 18, 2025, during a massive missile-drone attack, a video surfaced on social networks showing an F-16 of the Ukrainian Air Force shooting down a Russian Shahed-136 kamikaze drone with an AIM-9L missile.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p02] In a friendly fire incident on March 1, 2026, three USAF F-15E Strike Eagles were shot down by a F/A-18C Hornet of the Kuwaiti Air Force armed with AIM-9M and AIM-9X missiles.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p02] Naval Air Weapons Station China Lake experimented with Sidewinders in the air-to-ground mode including use as an anti-tank weapon.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p02] Starting from 2008, the AIM-9X demonstrated its ability as a successful light air-to-ground missile.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p02] In 2016, Diehl closed a deal with the Federal Office of Bundeswehr Equipment, Information Technology and In-Service Support to develop a laser guided Air-To-Ground variant of the Sidewinder missile based on the AIM-9L variant.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p02] In testing with the Swedish Defence Materiel Administration a Saab JAS 39 Gripen could hit one stationary and two moving targets.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p02] On 28 February 2018, the Iranian Islamic Revolutionary Guard Corps unveiled an anti-tank derivative of the Sidewinder missile named "Azarakhsh" intended for use by Bell AH-1J SeaCobra attack helicopters.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p02] Under the High Altitude Project, engineers at China Lake mated a Sidewinder warhead and seeker to a Sparrow rocket motor to experiment with usefulness of a larger motor, giving it a longer range.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p02] This was intended to provide the F-4 Phantom II the capability to intercept the Mikoyan MiG-25; eight prototype missiles were built.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p02] The **MIM-72 Chaparral** is an American-made self-propelled surface-to-air missile (SAM) based on the AIM-9 Sidewinder air-to-air missile system.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p02] In 2016, the AIM-9X was test fired from a Multi-Mission Launcher at the White Sands Missile Range in New Mexico, USA.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p02] During testing with the MML, the AIM-9X experienced issues with overheating.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p02] Army signed a contract with Dynetics to build prototypes for its Indirect Fires Protection Capability (IFPC), using an MML-based launcher firing the Sidewinder to counter UAVs and cruise missiles.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p02] It is planned to be put into service in 2023.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p02] In May 2019, the AIM-9X Block II was test fired from the National Advanced Surface to Air Missile System (NASAMS) at the Andøya Space Center in Norway.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p02] On 24 October 2023, a Ukrainian official said: "Those [AIM-9] missiles were out of operation...We found a way of launching them [Sidewinders] from the ground.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aim-9-sidewinder-p02] According to Budanov, the HUR began development on a MAGURA V5 unmanned surface vehicle armed with AIM-9 Sidewinders in January 2025.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aj-60a] The AJ-60A rocket motor was developed between 1999 and 2003 for use on the Atlas V.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aj-60a] On January 19, 2006 the New Horizons spacecraft to Pluto was launched directly into a solar-escape trajectory at 16.26 kilometers per second (58,536 km/h; 36,373 mph) from Cape Canaveral using an Atlas V version with 5 of these SRBs and Star 48B third stage.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aj-60a] *New Horizons* passed the Moon's orbit in just nine hours.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aj-60a] In 2015, ULA announced that the Atlas V will switch to new GEM 63 boosters produced by Northrop Grumman Innovation Systems.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aj-60a] (GEM 63XL, a stretched version of the GEM 63 booster is used on the Vulcan rocket.) The first Atlas V launched with GEM 63 boosters on November 13, 2020.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aj-60a] AJ-60A is a solid fueled rocket burning HTPB-based composite solid propellant.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aj-60a] The casing is composed of a graphite-epoxy composite, and the engine throat and nozzle are made of carbon-phenolic composite.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aj-60a] As configured for use on Atlas V, the nozzle is fixed at a 3 degree cant away from the attachment point, but Aerojet offers a variant with thrust vectoring capability.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aj-60a] The Atlas V configuration also features an inward slanting nosecone, but it is available with a conventional nosecone or none at all for use on other rockets.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aj-60a] The stages are designed to be transported by truck.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aj10] The **AJ10** is a hypergolic rocket engine manufactured by Aerojet Rocketdyne (previously Aerojet).
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aj10] It has been used to propel the upper stages of several launch vehicles, including the Delta II and Titan III.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aj10] Variants were and are used as the service propulsion engine for the Apollo command and service module, in the Space Shuttle Orbital Maneuvering System, and on the European Service Module – part of NASA's Orion spacecraft.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aj10] The AJ10 engine was first used in the Delta-A/Able second stage of the Vanguard rocket, in the **AJ10-37** configuration.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aj10] It was initially fueled by HNO3 and UDMH.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aj10] An AJ10 engine was first fired in flight during the third Vanguard launch, on 17 March 1958, which successfully placed the Vanguard 1 satellite into orbit.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aj10] The **AJ10-101** engine was used on an uprated version of the Able stage, used on Atlas-Able and Thor-Able rockets.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aj10] The first AJ10-101 flight, with a Thor-Able, occurred on 23 April 1958; however, the Thor failed before the upper Able stage fired.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aj10] The second flight, which saw the first in flight firing of an AJ10-101 engine, occurred on 10 July 1958.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aj10] The **AJ10-138** engine was originally developed for Vanguard and Able, and was flown from 1964 to 1980.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aj10] Two of these engines were used in the Titan III GTO Transtage, with thrust uprated from 7,800 lbf (35 kN) to 8,000 lbf (36 kN), and with a higher specific impulse of 311 s (3.05 km/s).
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aj10] The **AJ10-137** engine (20,500 lbf (91 kN) of thrust) was used in the Apollo service module's service propulsion system from first flight in 1966.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aj10] Trans-Earth injection, from lunar orbit, was the most critical usage of this engine during the Apollo program.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aj10] This version used Aerozine 50 (a 1:1 mix of UDMH and hydrazine) as fuel and nitrogen tetroxide (N2O4) as oxidizer, rather than the previous nitric acid/UDMH.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aj10] The **AJ10-118F** engine produced 9,000 lbf (40 kN) of thrust and was derived from the AJ10-138 engine used on the Transtage.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aj10] It was used by the Delta-F upper stage of the Delta 1000 *Straight Eight* series rocket, starting in 1972.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aj10] This version also used Aerozine 50 as fuel and nitrogen tetroxide (N2O4) as oxidizer.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aj10] The **AJ10-190** engine was used on the Space Shuttle Orbital Maneuvering System (OMS) for orbital insertion, on-orbit maneuvers, and de-orbiting, first flown in 1981.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aj10] They produced 26.7 kilonewtons (6,000 lbf) of thrust with a specific impulse (*I*sp) of 316 seconds.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aj10] Following the retirement of the Shuttle, these engines were repurposed for use on the Orion spacecraft's service module.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aj10] This variant uses CH6N2 as fuel, with nitrogen tetroxide (N2O4) as oxidizer.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aj10] The **AJ10-118K** engine was used on the Delta II rocket's upper stage, Delta-K.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aj10] It used Aerozine 50 as fuel and nitrogen tetroxide (N2O4) as oxidizer.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/aj10] The AJ10-118K engine variant was used from 1989 and retired at the conclusion of the ICESat-2 launch on 15 September 2018.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/alice-propellant] Aluminum-Ice Rocket Propellant, or **ALICE**, is a rocket propellant that consists of a frozen mixture of nano-aluminum powder and water (i.e. aluminum and ice).
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/alice-propellant] Aluminum has a stronger affinity for oxygen than most elements, which is most visible in aluminothermic reactions such as thermite.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/alice-propellant] This allows aluminum to burn with a large release of heat in substances that one normally considers to be inert, such as carbon dioxide and water.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/alice-propellant] However, aluminum combustion is normally hindered by the presence of a durable oxide layer that forms on the surface of aluminum particles, requiring significant heat to overcome.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/alice-propellant] Additionally, aluminum oxide condenses out of the exhaust stream at high temperature, leaving it (and its heat of condensation) unable to contribute to expansion without another gas present to function as a working fluid.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/alice-propellant] This generally has relegated aluminum's role in rocketry to that of being an additive to solid rocket propellants, increasing their density and combustion temperature, and stabilizing the burn.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/alice-propellant] The oxide layer in nano-aluminum powder, however, is thinner and easier to overcome than in that of larger particles, making the combustion of aluminum with water ice easier to ignite and sustain.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/alice-propellant] Furthermore, as the aluminum consumes the oxygen, it liberates hydrogen which functions as a low-molecular-mass working fluid to translate the heat of combustion (and subsequently condensation) into expansion and thrust.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/alice-propellant] The high density of the mixture allows for reduced tankage mass and high thrust.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/alice-propellant] ALICE has been proposed as a propellant well-suited for on-site production on outer space bodies such as the Moon, as both aluminum oxide (a source of aluminum) and water are abundant resources in the universe, while the high propellant density decreases the dry mass of the rocket.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/alice-propellant] Maintaining the propellant in a frozen state is relatively simple on most bodies in the Solar System, while other high-performance propellants often involve cryogenic fluids that can pose long-term storage problems.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/alice-propellant] One production method is to combine the powder with ice using resonant acoustic mixing, providing a consistent and homogenous result.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] A **solid-propellant rocket** or **solid rocket** is a rocket with a rocket engine that uses solid propellants (fuel/oxidizer).
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] The earliest rockets were solid-fuel rockets powered by gunpowder.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] The inception of gunpowder rockets in warfare can be credited to the medieval Chinese, and in the 13th century, the Mongols played a pivotal role in facilitating their westward adoption.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] All rockets used some form of solid or powdered propellant until the 20th century, when liquid-propellant rockets offered more efficient and controllable alternatives.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] Because of their simplicity and reliability, solid rockets are still used today in military armaments worldwide, model rockets, solid rocket boosters and on larger applications.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] Since solid-fuel rockets can remain in storage for an extended period without much propellant degradation, and since they almost always launch reliably, they have been frequently used in military applications such as missiles.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] The lower performance of solid propellants (as compared to liquids) does not favor their use as primary propulsion in modern medium-to-large launch vehicles customarily used for commercial satellites and major space probes.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] Solids are, however, frequently used as strap-on boosters to increase payload capacity or as spin-stabilized add-on upper stages when higher-than-normal velocities are required.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] Solid rockets are used as light launch vehicles for low Earth orbit (LEO) payloads under 2 tons or escape payloads up to 500 kilograms (1,100 lb).
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] A simple solid rocket motor consists of a casing, nozzle, grain (propellant charge), and igniter.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] The solid grain mass burns in a predictable fashion to produce exhaust gases, the flow of which is described by Taylor–Culick flow.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] The nozzle dimensions are calculated to maintain a design chamber pressure, while producing thrust from the exhaust gases.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] Once ignited, a simple solid rocket motor cannot be shut off, as it contains all the ingredients necessary for combustion within the chamber in which they are burned.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] More advanced solid rocket motors can be throttled, or extinguished and re-ignited, by control of the nozzle geometry or through the use of vent ports.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] Further, pulsed rocket motors that burn in segments, and that can be ignited upon command are available.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] Modern designs may also include a steerable nozzle for guidance, avionics, recovery hardware (parachutes), self-destruct mechanisms, APUs, controllable tactical motors, controllable divert and attitude control motors, and thermal management materials.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] The medieval Song dynasty Chinese invented the solid-propellant rocket.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] Each arrow took the form of a simple, solid-propellant rocket tube that was filled with gunpowder.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] One open end allowed the gas to escape and was attached to a long stick that acted as a guidance system for flight direction control.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] The first rockets with tubes of cast iron were used by the Kingdom of Mysore under Hyder Ali and Tipu Sultan in the 1750s.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] These rockets had a reach of targets up to a mile and a half away.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] These were extremely effective in the Second Anglo-Mysore War that ended in a humiliating defeat for the British East India Company.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] Word of the success of the Mysore rockets against the British triggered research in England, France, Ireland and elsewhere.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] When the British finally conquered the fort of Srirangapatana in 1799, hundreds of rockets were shipped off to the Royal Arsenal near London to be reverse-engineered.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] This led to the first industrial manufacture of military rockets with the Congreve rocket in 1804.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] In 1921 the Soviet research and development laboratory Gas Dynamics Laboratory began developing solid-propellant rockets, which resulted in the first launch in 1928, that flew for approximately 1,300 metres.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] These rockets were used in 1931 for the world's first successful use of rockets to assist take-off of aircraft.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] The research continued from 1933 by the Reactive Scientific Research Institute (RNII) with the development of the RS-82 and RS-132 rockets, including designing several variations for ground-to-air, ground-to-ground, air-to-ground and air-to-air combat.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] The earliest known use by the Soviet Air Force of aircraft-launched unguided anti-aircraft rockets in combat against heavier-than-air aircraft took place in August 1939, during the Battle of Khalkhin Gol.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] In June 1938, the RNII began developing a multiple rocket launcher based on the RS-132 rocket.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] In August 1939, the completed product was the BM-13 / Katyusha rocket launcher.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] Towards the end of 1938 the first significant large scale testing of the rocket launchers took place, 233 rockets of various types were used.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] A salvo of rockets could completely straddle a target at a range of 5,500 metres (3.4 mi).
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] By the end of World War II total production of rocket launchers reached about 10,000. with 12 million rockets of the RS type produced for the Soviet armed forces.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] In the United States modern castable composite solid rocket motors were invented by the American aerospace engineer Jack Parsons at Caltech in 1942 when he replaced double base propellant with roofing asphalt and potassium perchlorate.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] This made possible slow-burning rocket motors of adequate size and with sufficient shelf-life for jet-assisted take off applications.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] Charles Bartley, employed at JPL (Caltech), substituted curable synthetic rubber for the gooey asphalt, creating a flexible but geometrically stable load-bearing propellant grain that bonded securely to the motor casing.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] This made possible much larger solid rocket motors.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] Atlantic Research Corporation significantly boosted composite propellant Isp in 1954 by increasing the amount of powdered aluminium in the propellant to as much as 20%.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] Solid-propellant rocket technology got its largest boost in technical innovation, size and capability with the various mid-20th century government initiatives to develop increasingly capable military missiles.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] Many other governments also developed these military technologies over the next 50 years.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] Some designs have had solid rocket upper stages as well.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] Examples flying in the 2010s include the European Ariane 5, US Atlas V and Space Shuttle, and Japan's H-II.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] The largest solid rocket motors ever built were Aerojet's three 6.60-meter (260 in) monolithic solid motors cast in Florida.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] The nozzle throat was large enough to walk through standing up.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] The motor was capable of serving as a 1-to-1 replacement for the 8-engine Saturn I liquid-propellant first stage but was never used as such.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] Motor 260 SL-3 was of similar length and weight but had a maximum thrust of 24 MN (5,400,000 lbf) and a shorter duration.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] Design begins with the total impulse required, which determines the fuel and oxidizer mass.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] Grain geometry and chemistry are then chosen to satisfy the required motor characteristics.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] The following are chosen or solved simultaneously.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] The grain may or may not be bonded to the casing.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] Case-bonded motors are more difficult to design, since the deformation of the case and the grain under flight must be compatible.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] Common modes of failure in solid rocket motors include fracture of the grain, failure of case bonding, and air pockets in the grain.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] All of these produce an instantaneous increase in burn surface area and a corresponding increase in exhaust gas production rate and pressure, which may rupture the casing.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] Another failure mode is casing seal failure.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] Seals are required in casings that have to be opened to load the grain.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] Once a seal fails, hot gas will erode the escape path and result in failure.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] This was the cause of the Space Shuttle *Challenger* disaster.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] Solid rocket fuel deflagrates from the surface of exposed propellant in the combustion chamber.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] In this fashion, the geometry of the propellant inside the rocket motor plays an important role in the overall motor performance.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] As the surface of the propellant burns, the shape evolves (a subject of study in internal ballistics), most often changing the propellant surface area exposed to the combustion gases.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] The casing may be constructed from a range of materials.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] Cardboard is used for small black powder model motors, whereas aluminium is used for larger composite-fuel hobby motors.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] Steel was used for the space shuttle boosters.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] Filament-wound graphite epoxy casings are used for high-performance motors.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] The casing must be designed to withstand the pressure and resulting stresses of the rocket motor, possibly at elevated temperature.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] For design, the casing is considered a pressure vessel.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] To protect the casing from corrosive hot gases, a sacrificial thermal liner on the inside of the casing is often implemented, which ablates to prolong the life of the motor casing.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] A convergent-divergent design accelerates the exhaust gas out of the nozzle to produce thrust.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] The nozzle must be constructed from a material that can withstand the heat of the combustion gas flow.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] Often, heat-resistant carbon-based materials are used, such as amorphous graphite or reinforced carbon–carbon.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] Some designs include directional control of the exhaust.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] This can be accomplished by gimballing the nozzle, as in the Space Shuttle SRBs, by the use of jet vanes in the exhaust as in the V-2 rocket, or by liquid injection thrust vectoring (LITV).
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] LITV consists of injecting a liquid into the exhaust stream after the nozzle throat.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] The liquid then vaporizes, and in most cases chemically reacts, adding mass flow to one side of the exhaust stream and thus providing a control moment.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] For example, the Titan IIIC solid boosters injected dinitrogen tetroxide for LITV; the tanks can be seen on the sides of the rocket between the main center stage and the boosters.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] An early Minuteman first stage used a single motor with four gimballed nozzles to provide pitch, yaw, and roll control.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] A typical, well-designed ammonium perchlorate composite propellant (APCP) first-stage motor may have a vacuum specific impulse (*I*sp) as high as 285.6 seconds (2.801 km/s) (Titan IVB SRMU).
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] Propellant fractions are usually somewhat higher for (non-segmented) solid propellant first stages than for upper stages.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] Castor 120 and Castor 30 are 2.36 and 2.34 meters (93 and 92 in) in diameter, respectively, and serve as stages on the Athena IC and IIC commercial launch vehicles.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] A four-stage Athena II using Castor 120s as both first and second stages became the first commercially developed launch vehicle to launch a lunar probe (*Lunar Prospector*) in 1998.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] Solid rockets can provide high thrust for relatively low cost.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] For this reason, solids have been used as initial stages in rockets (for example the Space Shuttle), while reserving high specific impulse engines, especially less massive hydrogen-fueled engines, for higher stages.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] In addition, solid rockets have a long history as the final boost stage for satellites due to their simplicity, reliability, compactness and reasonably high mass fraction.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] A spin-stabilized solid rocket motor is sometimes added when extra velocity is required, such as for a mission to a comet or the outer solar system, because a spinner does not require a guidance system (on the newly added stage).
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] Thiokol's extensive family of mostly titanium-cased *Star* space motors has been widely used, especially on Delta launch vehicles and as spin-stabilized upper stages to launch satellites from the cargo bay of the Space Shuttle.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] *Star* motors have propellant fractions as high as 94.6% but add-on structures and equipment reduce the operating mass fraction by 2% or more.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] Higher performing solid rocket propellants are used in large strategic missiles (as opposed to commercial launch vehicles).
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] HMX, C4H8N4(NO2)4, a nitramine with greater energy than ammonium perchlorate, was used in the propellant of the Peacekeeper ICBM and is the main ingredient in NEPE-75 propellant used in the Trident II D-5 Fleet Ballistic Missile.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] It is because of explosive hazard that the higher energy military solid propellants containing HMX are not used in commercial launch vehicles except when the LV is an adapted ballistic missile already containing HMX propellant (Minotaur IV and V based on the retired Peacekeeper ICBMs).
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] The Naval Air Weapons Station at China Lake, California, developed a new compound, C6H6N6(NO2)6, called simply CL-20 (China Lake compound #20).
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] Compared to HMX, CL-20 has 14% more energy per mass, 20% more energy per volume, and a higher oxygen-to-fuel ratio.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] One of the motivations for development of these very high energy density military solid propellants is to achieve mid-course exo-atmospheric ABM capability from missiles small enough to fit in existing ship-based below-deck vertical launch tubes and air-mobile truck-mounted launch tubes.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] CL-20 propellant compliant with Congress' 2004 insensitive munitions (IM) law has been demonstrated and may, as its cost comes down, be suitable for use in commercial launch vehicles, with a very significant increase in performance compared with the currently favored APCP solid propellants.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] An attractive attribute for military use is the ability for solid rocket propellant to remain loaded in the rocket for long durations and then be reliably launched at a moment's notice.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] Black powder (gunpowder) is composed of charcoal (fuel), potassium nitrate (oxidizer), and sulfur (fuel and catalyst).
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] It is one of the oldest pyrotechnic compositions with application to rocketry.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] In modern times, black powder finds use in low-power model rockets (such as Estes and Quest rockets), as it is cheap and fairly easy to produce.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] The fuel grain is typically a mixture of pressed fine powder (into a solid, hard slug), with a burn rate that is highly dependent upon exact composition and operating conditions.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] The specific impulse of black powder is low, around 80 s (0.78 km/s).
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] The grain is sensitive to fracture and, therefore, catastrophic failure.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] Black powder does not typically find use in motors above 40 newtons (9.0 pounds-force) thrust.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] ZS is most often employed as a novelty propellant as the rocket accelerates extremely quickly leaving a spectacular large orange fireball behind it.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] DB propellants are composed of two monopropellant fuel components where one typically acts as a high-energy (yet unstable) monopropellant and the other acts as a lower-energy stabilizing (and gelling) monopropellant.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] In typical circumstances, nitroglycerin is dissolved in a nitrocellulose gel and solidified with additives.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] DB propellants are implemented in applications where minimal smoke is required yet a medium-high Isp of roughly 235 s (2.30 km/s) is required.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] The addition of metal fuels (such as aluminium) can increase performance to around 250 s (2.5 km/s), though metal oxide nucleation in the exhaust can turn the smoke opaque.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] A powdered oxidizer and powdered metal fuel are intimately mixed and immobilized with a rubbery binder (that also acts as a fuel).
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] Composite propellants are often either ammonium-nitrate-based (ANCP) or ammonium-perchlorate-based (APCP).
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] Aluminium is used as fuel because it has a reasonable specific energy density, a high volumetric energy density, and is difficult to ignite accidentally.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] Composite propellants are cast, and retain their shape after the rubber binder, such as Hydroxyl-terminated polybutadiene (HTPB), cross-links (solidifies) with the aid of a curative additive.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] Because of its high performance, moderate ease of manufacturing, and moderate cost, APCP finds widespread use in space, military, and amateur rockets, whereas cheaper and less efficient ANCP finds use in amateur rocketry and gas generators.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] Ammonium dinitramide, NH4N(NO2)2, is being considered as a 1-to-1 chlorine-free substitute for ammonium perchlorate in composite propellants.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] Unlike ammonium nitrate, ADN can be substituted for AP without a loss in motor performance.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] Polyurethane-bound aluminium-APCP solid fuel was used in the submarine-launched Polaris missiles.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] It developed a specific impulse of 242 seconds (2.37 km/s) at sea level or 268 seconds (2.63 km/s) in a vacuum.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] The 2005–2009 Constellation Program was to use a similar PBAN-bound APCP.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] In 2009, a group succeeded in creating a propellant of water and nanoaluminium (ALICE).
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] In general, rocket candy propellants are an oxidizer (typically potassium nitrate) and a sugar fuel (typically dextrose, sorbitol, or sucrose) that are cast into shape by gently melting the propellant constituents together and pouring or packing the amorphous colloid into a mold.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] Candy propellants generate a low-medium specific impulse of roughly 130 s (1.3 km/s) and, thus, are used primarily by amateur and experimental rocketeers.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] Typical HEC propellants start with a standard composite propellant mixture (such as APCP) and add a high-energy explosive to the mix.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] This extra component usually is in the form of small crystals of RDX or HMX, both of which have higher energy than ammonium perchlorate.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] Despite a modest increase in specific impulse, implementation is limited due to the increased hazards of the high-explosive additives.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] Composite modified double base propellants start with a nitrocellulose/nitroglycerin double base propellant as a binder and add solids (typically ammonium perchlorate (AP) and powdered aluminium) normally used in composite propellants.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] The ammonium perchlorate makes up the oxygen deficit introduced by using nitrocellulose, improving the overall specific impulse.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] The aluminium improves specific impulse as well as combustion stability.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] High performing propellants such as NEPE-75 used to fuel the Trident II D-5 SLBM replace most of the AP with polyethylene glycol-bound HMX, further increasing specific impulse.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] The mixing of composite and double base propellant ingredients has become so common as to blur the functional definition of double base propellants.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] One of the most active areas of solid propellant research is the development of high-energy, minimum-signature propellant using C6H6N6(NO2)6 CL-20 (China Lake compound #20), which has 14% higher energy per mass and 20% higher energy density than HMX.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] The new propellant has been successfully developed and tested in tactical rocket motors.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] The propellant is non-polluting: acid-free, solid particulates-free, and lead-free.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] It is also smokeless and has only a faint shock diamond pattern that is visible in the otherwise transparent exhaust.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] Without the bright flame and dense smoke trail produced by the burning of aluminized propellants, these smokeless propellants all but eliminate the risk of giving away the positions from which the missiles are fired.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] The new CL-20 propellant is shock-insensitive (hazard class 1.3) as opposed to current HMX smokeless propellants which are highly detonable (hazard class 1.1).
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] CL-20 is considered a major breakthrough in solid rocket propellant technology but has yet to see widespread use because costs remain high.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] Electric solid propellants (ESPs) are a family of high performance plastisol solid propellants that can be ignited and throttled by the application of electric current.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] Unlike conventional rocket motor propellants that are difficult to control and extinguish, ESPs can be ignited reliably at precise intervals and durations.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] It requires no moving parts and the propellant is insensitive to flames or electrical sparks.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] Solid propellant rocket motors can be bought for use in model rocketry; they are normally small cylinders of black powder fuel with an integral nozzle and optionally a small charge that is set off when the propellant is exhausted after a time delay.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] This charge can be used to trigger a camera, or deploy a parachute.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] Without this charge and delay, the motor may ignite a second stage (black powder only).
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] In amateur rocketry, "candy" propellants are common because they offer relative safety and ease of production, ingredients that are readily available publicly, and a higher specific impulse than blackpowder motors.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] In mid- and high-power rocketry, commercially made APCP motors are widely used.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] They can be designed as either single-use or reloadables.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] These motors are available in impulse ranges from "A" (1.26 Ns– 2.50 Ns) to "O" (20.48 kNs – 40.96 kNs), from several manufacturers.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] They are manufactured in standardized diameters and varying lengths depending on required impulse.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] Different propellant formulations are available to produce different thrust profiles, as well as special effects such as colored flames, smoke trails, or large quantities of sparks (produced by adding titanium sponge to the mix).
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] Almost all sounding rockets use solid motors.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] Due to reliability, ease of storage and handling, solid rockets are used on missiles and ICBMs.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] Solid rockets are suitable for launching small payloads to orbital velocities, especially if three or more stages are used.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] Many of these are based on repurposed ICBMs.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] Gravity-1 is the largest-payload-capacity rocket to get into orbit with only solid rocket motors.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] Larger liquid-fueled orbital rockets often use solid rocket boosters to gain enough initial thrust to launch the fully fueled rocket.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] Solid fuel is also used for some upper stages, particularly the Star 37 (sometimes referred to as the "Burner" upper stage) and the Star 48 (sometimes referred to as the "Payload Assist Module", or PAM), both manufactured originally by Thiokol, and today by Northrop Grumman.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] They are used to lift large payloads to intended orbits (such as the Global Positioning System satellites), or smaller payloads to interplanetary—or even interstellar—trajectories.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] Another solid-fuel upper stage, used by the Space Shuttle and the Titan IV, was the Boeing-manufactured Inertial Upper Stage (IUS).
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] Some rockets, like the Antares (manufactured by Northrop Grumman), have mandatory solid-fuel upper stages.
[src:solid-propellant-rocket/solid-propellant-rocket] The Antares rocket uses the Northrop Grumman-manufactured Castor 30 as an upper stage.
